# Pattern for referencing ADRs from a Detailed Design.
# ADRs are flat and cross-cutting; the DD references them by id, never inlines them.

# === FRONT-MATTER FORM ===
# Inside detailed_design.md YAML front-matter:

governing_adrs:
  - <<ADR-NNN-name>>      # short title — e.g., "ADR-008: bearer-JWT authn at gateway"
  - <<ADR-NNN-name>>      # short title — e.g., "ADR-019: idempotency-key under at-least-once delivery"


# === BODY-CITATION PATTERN ===
# At each spot in the body where a governing ADR's decision lands, cite the ADR.
# The DD applies the decision; the ADR justifies it.

# Example — inside a postcondition:
#   on_success:
#     - "Duplicate-key calls return the first response byte-for-byte and do not
#        re-commit (per ADR-019)."

# Example — inside a recovery strategy:
#   recovery: retry (max 2; exponential backoff; idempotency-assumption per ADR-019)

# Example — inside a state-transition action:
#   action: "Emit OrderPlaced via outbox relay (per ADR-019 — at-least-once delivery)"


# === STUB FOR DECISIONS NOT YET ADR'D ===
# When DD authoring surfaces a decision meeting all three criteria (load-bearing AND
# cross-cutting AND hard-to-reverse) but no ADR exists yet, emit a stub:

# [NEEDS-ADR: <one-sentence decision> — extract before finalising]

# Examples:
# [NEEDS-ADR: choose at-least-once vs exactly-once delivery for OrderPlaced events
#             — extract before finalising]
# [NEEDS-ADR: choose HMAC-SHA256 over JWT for session token signature
#             — extract before finalising]

# Finalising means: ADR authored → ADR id added to `governing_adrs:` → stub replaced
# with the body-citation pattern above.

# A `governing_adrs:` list with no body citations is decoration.
# A body citation with no `governing_adrs:` entry is an unresolvable reference.
